commit_message:
Add support for module ordering on apply

Modules currently are applied in any order, however operators may wish
to control the order that modules are applied to ensure proper
functionality.

This spec addresses this issue.

References: blueprint module-management-ordering
Change-Id: I12afa490033f018a8feda874b59e1e219ec96d4a

commit_message:
Fixes for dlrn gate repo injection while using devmode

- invert dlrn repo injection and update order
- check if overcloud image is already available before trying to extract
- don't try to inject overcloud image if it wasn't extracted

Change-Id: Iee49ca5e08ece0917ee42d62054da0d0b6f9882c

commit_message:
Do not put real hostname and IP address to manila config sample

For the moment, building manila configuration sample, we get real
hostname and IP address of host that runs "genconfig" tox job. It
should not be exposed. So, hide it using "sample_default" arg for
appropriate options.

TrivialFix

commit_message:
Improve Keystone v3 token support

Now keystoneauth uses HTTP_X_TENANT_NAME/ID only even if v3 token uses for
backward compatibility. There is no problem with current behavior because
keystonemiddleware set same value on the headers but the headers are
specified as deprecated so this patch allows to support HTTP_X_PROJECT_NAME/ID
in addition to HTTP_X_TENANT_NAME/ID.

Change-Id: Ie5e02067a59e18f1ac215f51429863bdd42f729f

commit_message:
Correct reraising of exception

When an exception is caught and rethrown, it should call 'raise'
without any arguments because it shows the place where an exception
occured initially instead of place where the exception was re-raised.

Co-Authored-By: Songming Yan <yan.songming@zte.com.cn>

Change-Id: I49f9847fbc0733b97a99637e2400f9dbb21182e3

commit_message:
Add Python 3.5 classifier and venv

Now that there is a passing gate job, we can claim support for
Python 3.5 in the classifier. This patch also adds the convenience
py35 venv.

Change-Id: Iae291361db5473c49fefa99e24d3d058fb8cd9ac

Improve help text of flavors config options

1. Added more verbose to flavor configuration options
2. Fixed syntax for consistency

Implements blueprint centralize-config-options-newton

commit_message:
Fix Freezer Agent Logging

Standardize on oslo.log.
Log exception stack traces where appropriate.
Add logging to all files.
Remove '[*]' from log messages.
Log command line arguments at Freezer Agent start
so that errors can be traced to specific invocations.

Leave scheduler module mostly unchanged because it
is doing python logging configuration.

Change-Id: I23de0558409e63978303963d592a4e5ee4dee2b5
(cherry picked from commit 00db2b0)

commit_message:
Fix variable name ENABLE_TEMPEST to UPGRADE_TEMPEST

It seems the intent is to upgrade tempest only if asked for[1][2]

This patch renames the ENABLE_TEMPEST variable to UPGRADE_TEMPEST to
avoid unnecessary tempest upgrade.

[1] https://github.com/openstack-dev/grenade/blob/master/grenade.sh#L253--#L257
[2] https://github.com/openstack-dev/grenade/blob/master/grenade.sh#L306

Change-Id: I4c59f67bfb8dcba64b3d1d90b4ad5a4c134fa55a

Remove setting project name on clientmanager

Best I can see this was copied across from OSC and are not used anywhere
in osc-lib. We can remove them.

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-07-14 06:41:04.000000000', 'message': 'Fix bug for write-kube-os-config.sh

In file write-kube-os-config.sh, the bug is in line below
AUTH_URL=$(echo "$AUTH_URL" | tr -s "v3" "v2")
this command is used to change v3 to v2,but it will change any "3" to
"2". For example:
AUTH_URL=10.43.166.108:5000/v3
it will be changed to 10.42.166.108:5000/v2, where 43 is also changed
to 42.

Change-Id: Ia329b983ba59856783f2873722c9ade418d49cea
Closes-Bug: #1599703
'}]
commit_message:
Fix bug for write-kube-os-config.sh

In file write-kube-os-config.sh, the bug is in line below
AUTH_URL=$(echo "$AUTH_URL" | tr -s "v3" "v2")
this command is used to change v3 to v2,but it will change any "3" to
"2". For example:
AUTH_URL=10.43.166.108:5000/v3
it will be changed to 10.42.166.108:5000/v2, where 43 is also changed
to 42.

Change-Id: Ia329b983ba59856783f2873722c9ade418d49cea
Closes-Bug: #1599703

commit_message:
Replace "LOG.info(_" with "LOG.info(_LI"

Follow http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html:
If a common message is not being used, they should each betreated
separately with respect to choosing a marker function.So this patch
is to fix it.

Change-Id: If7a74ce983ad0c7f4cab057cadd7d20ef3067fcd
Closes-Bug: #1600788

[{'created': '2016-07-06 19:25:24.000000000', 'message': 'go: storage policies

This implements storage policies (as best I understand them).
It turned into a pretty big patch and changes a bunch of stuff.

There's a lot of plumbing of policies into functions that choose an
"objects" directory.

The replicator and auditor also handle any "replication" policies.
Those may get abstracted later on so you can register auditor and
replicator equivalents for non-replication object engines.

Request routing can take policies into account.  This is so that
something like "REPLICATE" calls can be routed to the correct object
engine, since they're instantiated per-policy.

They're instantiated per-policy so they can get the configs for their
policy, which swift doesn't really do, but I think could be useful.

Change-Id: Ia90664f9b178a29e1061bb03d0dd442ba6636c73
'}]
commit_message:
go: storage policies

This implements storage policies (as best I understand them).
It turned into a pretty big patch and changes a bunch of stuff.

There's a lot of plumbing of policies into functions that choose an
"objects" directory.

The replicator and auditor also handle any "replication" policies.
Those may get abstracted later on so you can register auditor and
replicator equivalents for non-replication object engines.

Request routing can take policies into account.  This is so that
something like "REPLICATE" calls can be routed to the correct object
engine, since they're instantiated per-policy.

They're instantiated per-policy so they can get the configs for their
policy, which swift doesn't really do, but I think could be useful.

Change-Id: Ia90664f9b178a29e1061bb03d0dd442ba6636c73

i'm really not sure about this as a solution.  it is kind of confusing and doesn't seem to solve the root problem. if I use --include-children, i still get the error messages in the bug.

The reason I saw confusing is that I'm basically a giant idiot and this command doesn't seem very idiot proof.  As an idiot, I have to understand all the parent child relationships and then go index them one by one or figure them out and include them all. It seems like my typical idiot self would easily mess this up.

As an idiot, I'd probably rather be able to just tell it to index a specific type and then get the children by default (exclude-children) be the option. 

Or maybe since the output is still broken and shows all resource types, that confuses me.

We probably should chat about this.  Sorry I missed you on IRC today. Every time I go into the office, my availability gets really spotty from all of the random conversations that happen."}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2016-06-21 22:55:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

- gate-searchlight-python34-searchlight http://logs.openstack.org/42/332242/4/check/gate-searchlight-python34-searchlight/fa14b2f/ : SUCCESS in 4m 15s'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2016-06-24 19:26:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

This seems to fix the version conflict. I didn't do a massive amount of regression testing. That said, I've been thinking about this more since our discussion in IRC.  Here are my thoughts:

1) You are right that exposing parent child does expose an implementation detail. So, if we can avoid it we probably should.  That said, the clients are going to have to know this anyway for doing queries. It might create a false sense of safety when trying to get all of foo by just doing OS::Foo::Parent and missing types that aren't in any type of a tree.

2) If I just want to index a single type or specific types, this makes a lot of sense and should be more performant.

3) If I want to index a complete service and only it, it is a pain and will be error prone for upgrades **.  Here are my options

 Option A) In order for me to say re-index all of neutron, I'd have to do this:

 searchlight-manage index sync --type OS::Neutron::Network,OS::Neutron::Subnet,OS::Neutron::Router,OS::Neutron::Port,OS::NeutronSecurityGroup,OS::Neutron::FloatingIP

That is error prone and difficult to remember.  Then as soon as we add a new Neutron type, the command is invalid. **

 Option B) Create a config file that has just the resource types I want to be indexed enabled and use it for indexing.  In production, it actually can more closely mimic how services are deployed with resource groups. E.g., if I have a listener set up for just Neutron, I can do that via config file and run searchlight manage with the same config file.  If I want to re-index the entire resource group, I should specify the config file to use. Interestingly, this means a globally installed searchlight-manage command would be a problem.

This will be really to do in dev / test envs. Also, if I choose to group neutron and nova into a resource group and use the same config file, I'd still need to specify resource types if I want to just reindex neutron. This would be error prone. **

As a developer (who will use this more often than any deployer), I would like to be able to just update all of neutron when a patch comes in touching multiple neutron resource types. I use this now as a simplification.

All of this got me to thinking that we could either support * syntax e.g.

 searchlight-manage index sync --type OS::Neutron::*

or just support parsing at the "namespace" level.

 searchlight-manage index sync --type OS::Neutron::

** All of the above has led me to also realize that upgrade scenarios may be problematic for deployers, particularly because we seem to just enable plugins by default or not.  If you enable them by default, a deployer who had a config file per service will suddenly have to update every single config file to disable the new plugin (At least according to documentation:

http://docs.openstack.org/developer/searchlight/plugins.html#non-inheritable-common-configuration-options)

It all kinds of make me think searchlight-manage & searchlight-listener should allow you to specify the resource group via command line. This way you wouldn't need a different config file per service process instance.

Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2016-06-24 19:32:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

BTW, sorry for my typically poor grammar and formatting making it harder to understand. I can correct and re-post if needed. :('}, {'account_id': 10063, 'date': '2016-06-24 19:41:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

In the interests of fixing the bug this patch addresses, i'd be inclined to make those separate improvements.

I think supporting OS::Neutron makes a lot of sense as a shortcut for the scenario you mention.

In terms of enabling plugins by default, the other option is to enable nothing by default; potentially we could make this an option at the root level (i.e. make 'enabled' an overridable option) but we still have to pick our side. Remember that a deployer will always have to create a config file; the autogenerated one on its own is not valid, so if we have it documented that the default is opt-in, but you can make it opt-out, that might be ok.

Specifying resource types for the listener i'm not sure about; I'd have to think about the use cases of why you might choose to do that.

What I don't want to do, however, is introduce any of these behaviors in this patch, but I'm fine with them being separate BPs."}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2016-06-24 19:59:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

[resource_plugin:os_cinder_volume]
resource_group_name = sl-cinder
admin_only_fields = status,bootable
[resource_plugin:os_cinder_snapshot]
resource_group_name = sl-cinder
[resource_plugin:os_designate_zone]
resource_group_name = sl-designate
[resource_plugin:os_glance_images]
resource_group_name = sl-glance
[resource_plugin:os_neutron_net]
resource_group_name = sl-neutron
[resource_plugin:os_neutron_port]
resource_group_name = sl-neutron
[resource_plugin:os_neutron_subnet]
resource_group_name = sl-neutron
[resource_plugin:os_neutron_router]
resource_group_name = sl-neutron
[resource_plugin:os_neutron_security_group]
resource_group_name = sl-neutron
[resource_plugin:os_nova_server]
resource_group_name = sl-nova
[resource_plugin:os_nova_hypervisor]
resource_group_name = sl-nova

When I run this command:
searchlight-manage --config-file etc/searchlight.conf index sync --type OS::Cinder::Snapshot,OS::Nova::Server,OS::Neutron::Port

I get this output:

All resource types within Resource Group "sl-neutron" must be re-indexed.

Any types marked with * will be reindexed from existing Elasticsearch data.

Resource types (and aliases) matching selection:

OS::Cinder::Volume (sl-cinder) *
    --> OS::Cinder::Snapshot (sl-cinder)
OS::Neutron::Net (sl-neutron) *
    --> OS::Neutron::Subnet (sl-neutron) *
    --> OS::Neutron::Port (sl-neutron)
OS::Neutron::Router (sl-neutron) *
OS::Nova::Hypervisor (sl-nova) *
OS::Nova::Server (sl-nova)

Indexing will NOT delete existing data or mapping(s). It will reindex all resources. 
Use '--force' to suppress this message.
OK to continue? [y/n]: n

This is incorrect. The first line should say something like this:

All resource types within Resource Groups "sl-cinder, sl-nova, sl-neutron" must be re-indexed.

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-06-21 16:41:23.000000000', 'message': "Fix --type handling for indexing parent plugins

When --type is used to index a parent plugin, any child plugins are also
indexed from their APIs, and then the data's copied into the new index,
causing conflict errors. This patch adds '--include-children' to the
index sync command which defaults to False such that by default only
plugins in --type are indexed from their APIs. When set to true, child
plugins are not included in the index-to-index copy step.

Removes the setup_data argument from PluginBase.initial_indexing since
it had no use following earlier refactorings.

Change-Id: Idbec6d3bf663cda7eeb6ab4be19b73d41fa2c8da
Closes-Bug: #1584148

When --type is used to index a parent plugin, any child plugins are also
indexed from their APIs, and then the data's copied into the new index,
causing conflict errors. This patch simplifies indexing such that child
plugins are not indexed as a part of indexing the parent since the
reason for doing that in the past was refactored some time ago. Only
types specified in --type will be indexed from API; others from an old
index.

This patch removes initial_indexing since it no longer has use, and
renames setup_data to index_initial_data.

commit_message:
Fix --type handling for indexing parent plugins

When --type is used to index a parent plugin, any child plugins are also
indexed from their APIs, and then the data's copied into the new index,
causing conflict errors. This patch simplifies indexing such that child
plugins are not indexed as a part of indexing the parent since the
reason for doing that in the past was refactored some time ago. Only
types specified in --type will be indexed from API; others from an old
index.

(See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/295538/)

This patch removes initial_indexing since it no longer has use, and
renames setup_data to index_initial_data.

Patch also changes the index sync diagnostic text to indicate (with a *)
plugins which will be indexed from existing Elasticsearch data when
--type is specified.

Change-Id: Idbec6d3bf663cda7eeb6ab4be19b73d41fa2c8da
Closes-Bug: #1584148

commit_message:
Do not fail the playbook when libvirt network auto start fails

This is a workaround for the following error message.
'Requested operation is not valid: cannot set autostart for transient network'
This seems to occur mainly on RHEL virthosts and has not been very apparent
in ci.centos or traditional oooq deployments.

For more details see:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/tripleo-quickstart/+bug/1581676

Related-Bug: 1581676

Change-Id: If1a59627c4c8a7d0bb6cf01b17853d5c5a295403

commit_message:
Add revision_number to standard attr for OVO

This adds the revision number field to the standard attributes
OVO code. All standard attribute OVO version numbers needed to
be bumped but the version numbers were kept the same since the
changed objects haven't been released yet.

Partially-Implements: blueprint push-notifications
Change-Id: I864fe6964b32c7801465e8ebf45ce48f3e8e0cc9

commit_message:
Use plugins repo version of the human_log callback plugin

With the implementation of https://review.openstack.org/321331 the
human_log callback plugin is now part of the plugins repo.

This patch removes the retrofitted version in tox in favor of using
the version from the plugins repo instead.

Change-Id: I02b8646a867a39c555cf821e4680d93d57b27b23

commit_message:
delete stale ovsdb table entries from mysql db

whenever l2gateway_agnet.ini is reconfigured to the same ovsdb identifier
but different IP, then we need to clean the mysql db entries from earlier
configured ovsdb_identifier and IP.

For Ex: l2gateway_agent is connected to "ovsdb1:10.10.10.10:6632",
but when you change l2gateway_agent.ini to "ovsdb1:20.20.20.20:6632",
then the mysql entries related to "ovsdb1:10.10.10.10:6632" should be cleaned.

Change-Id: I72cd5a5e2ea27c2a6b37865c3517e614f901aecf
Closes-Bug:1588809
(cherry picked from commit af5c24232ee27aa9b5b4b5cf49046d1c889e89a4)

commit_message:
Remove 'nodes' key from serializer for 10.0

'nodes' data is deprecated so must be removed from 10.0 version
serializer output. The change was moved to separate serializer class in
order to maintain compatibility with previously deployed 9.0 clusters
after upgrade to 10.0.

Change-Id: I8fef591908cd8b1e4ace5502bb1e80cb37786c6e
Related-Bug: #1531128

commit_message:
Add max_length to URIOpt

Currently StrOpt has a max_length parameter to restrict the length
of the value, but URIOpt does not. The keystone project actually
has use for a max_length to restrict a URI used for the SAML2
entity ID.

Reference patch:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/341514

Change-Id: I39d012b0b7ebeddf6067016487ac8258461dda30

commit_message:
Cleanup/standardize usage of tags

The numerous tags within the role have been condensed
to two tags: gnocchi-install and gnocchi-config

These tags have been chosen as they are namespaced
and cover the two major functions of the role.

Documentation has been updated to inform how each tag
influences the function of the role.

Change-Id: Ie621d30c57d030577d7a1f01d2225ea4b17220a4

commit_message:
Use plugins repo version of the human_log callback plugin

With the implementation of https://review.openstack.org/321331 the
human_log callback plugin is now part of the plugins repo.

This patch removes the retrofitted version in tox in favor of using
the version from the plugins repo instead.

Change-Id: Ied88dd355c41e48566c6179333930d625dc9637c

[{'created': '2016-07-11 19:21:48.000000000', 'message': "Don't apply config fixture to auth_token.CONF

auth_token.CONF is simply the global oslo.config conf object linked into
the auth_token module. It is not intended for public use and has
recently been moved.

We can mock exactly the same entries without having to reach into
auth_token middleware and should do that instead.

Closes-Bug: #1600529
Change-Id: I5e8a481f37a7b409e491ce893a0e898d5085cc75
(cherry picked from commit 0bd4a6c286c9d867d04f77b17abf4862f3095742)

auth_token.CONF is simply the global oslo.config conf object linked into
the auth_token module. It is not intended for public use and has
recently been moved.

commit_message:
Don't apply config fixture to auth_token.CONF

auth_token.CONF is simply the global oslo.config conf object linked into
the auth_token module. It is not intended for public use and has
recently been moved.

We can mock exactly the same entries without having to reach into
auth_token middleware and should do that instead.

* Also contains this change:
  Update quota_utils with import for keystone_auth
  Author: Ryan McNair <rdmcnair@us.ibm.com>
  Change-Id: I3ebb9979d37f62db161e2929fe2cff5a8ba2bf96
  (cherry picked from commit 4d66d2e833b86156e49ee34da49f7d6040945af1)
  Conflicts:
        cinder/quota_utils.py

Closes-Bug: #1600529
Change-Id: I5e8a481f37a7b409e491ce893a0e898d5085cc75
(cherry picked from commit 0bd4a6c286c9d867d04f77b17abf4862f3095742)
Conflicts:
	cinder/tests/unit/api/contrib/test_quotas.py
	cinder/tests/unit/test_quota.py
	cinder/tests/unit/test_quota_utils.py

commit_message:
Add a py35 environment to tox

Infra will start running python35 jobs soon [1], targeting to replace
the current python34 jobs. This is due to the change from Ubuntu Trusty
to Xenial, where only python3.5 will be available.

Adding py35 environment to supported envlist.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/336272

Change-Id: I53801ba018a62e780c8ab66de51257fe019a99f0

commit_message:
Cleanup/standardize usage of tags

The numerous tags within the role have been condensed
to two tags: designate-install and designate-config

These tags have been chosen as they are namespaced
and cover the two major functions of the role.

Documentation has been updated to inform how each tag
influences the function of the role.

Change-Id: I700b80bce2a8a761d341ca9cdc51398328966287

commit_message:
service validation: log output on failures

When validating a service, it's useful to have logs when exec output
fails.
This patch adds this feature.

Change-Id: I43c9eff8516ea562bf9bde8d5651ddceeb496163

commit_message:
Make rabbitmq inventory group configurable

The default value of "rabbitmq_all" remains, but this
change should allow deployers to target the role to multiple
groups now.

Change-Id: Idc1bc44b005f09f9dc7eb9778719a8ba92756c06
Implements: blueprint multi-rabbitmq-clusters

commit_message:
Fix Unicode error printing extra-specs

If type-key is set to unicode the command cinder extra-specs-list
fails with the ERROR: 'ascii' codec can't encode characters in position.
This patch fixes it.

Change-Id: Id82bfbe8870351605f53c7ca029b9aa7e6089f6a
Closes-Bug: #1568937

command, because it isn't just english words.

@Naohiro. Thanks for introducing new feature. I think there is a problem with "soft" power actions. External power controllers (like in UPS) do not support "soft off" at all (or require a configured daemon in the OS, it can be not configured). But change power state is async. User should look at "last_error" or log for check "soft" actions support. IMO Ironic should return error immediately it the response if driver does not support "soft" actions.'}, {'account_id': 7711, 'date': '2015-06-05 11:21:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

 > 1) how to interrupt the on-going SOFT POWER OFF or INJECT NMI to
 >    implement cancel or force hard power off?

Patch #4 of [1] has a POC implementation of CANCEL_POWER_OFF_SOFT.

I confirmed it works by curl command.

The solution I chose is CSP channels.

Please have a look at the source code.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/207897/4

 > 2) how to judge if INJECT NMI has been completed.

In terms of this issue, I'd like NOT TO IMPLEMENT for ipmitool

driver. Because general BMC is not capable to get OS status.

Each vendor should provide INJECT NMI capability in vendor specific way.

What do you think?

Best regards,

(6 comments)

This has come a very long ways -- thank you to all for the hard work on it.

I have a few questions inline, particularly around what it means for these operations to time out. It does not make sense for the Node's power_state to be set to ERROR -- there is a periodic task which will simply overwrite that, and set the power state to what ever the Node's actual power state is, when this transition is marked as completed.

Instead, what I believe should happen is, when the SOFT_OFF times out, it should automatically escalate to a HARD_POWER_OFF + POWER_ON.

I also do not understand how Ironic will determine whether an INJECT_NMI request has been completed vs. when it has timed out. AIUI, Ironic can only send this command to the BMC -- it has no way to know if the OS has received or honored the request. Therefore, it is illogical to discuss how this command would timeout (either it is received by the BMC or we encounter some error communicating to the BMC)."}, {'account_id': 13719, 'date': '2016-04-14 08:09:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

(9 comments)

Devananda,

Thanks for taking your time to review this spec and giving invaluable feedback.

 > I have a few questions inline, particularly around what it means for
 > these operations to time out. It does not make sense for the Node's
 > power_state to be set to ERROR -- there is a periodic task which will
 > simply overwrite that, and set the power state to what ever the Node's
 > actual power state is, when this transition is marked as completed.

Please find my reply inline.
In short, I'd like to propose to enter into maintenance mode if we got error.

 > Instead, what I believe should happen is, when the SOFT_OFF times out,
 > it should automatically escalate to a HARD_POWER_OFF + POWER_ON.

We could escalate to a HARD_POWER_OFF + POWER_ON.
But how about entering into the maintenance mode, and give a chance for user to open the console via shellinthebox or whatever.

 > 
 > I also do not understand how Ironic will determine whether an
 > INJECT_NMI request has been completed vs. when it has timed out. AIUI,
 > Ironic can only send this command to the BMC -- it has no way to know
 > if the OS has received or honored the request. Therefore, it is
 > illogical to discuss how this command would timeout (either it is
 > received by the BMC or we encounter some error communicating to the
 > BMC). 

I'd like to propose to enter into maintenance mode just after issuing INJECT_NMI without any condition especially in case of IPMIPower.
Because user has to start investigation by logging on the OS as soon as taking a kernel dump.
Regardless of happening error or not, user has to log on and Ironic should not control the power.
So the maintenance mode seems to solve all of concerns we have, I believe. WDYT?

Best regards,
Naohiro"}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2016-04-20 23:16:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

Naohiro,

For this conversation, I am assuming that users will interact with their cloud through Nova, and _not_ through Ironic. If that is not your starting assumption, please let me know and I will re-read the spec with that in mind.

When a Node is placed in maintenance mode, this is a signal to the cloud operator that something is wrong with the _hardware_ and Ironic is no longer able to manage it. Status polling stops. The Node is removed from Nova's resource pool. Certain actions (like provisioning an instance) are not allowed on the Node. The end-user (who created the Nova Instance that is now running on this Node) can not interact with the Ironic API -- and therefore, can not clear the maintenance mode flag. 

So, this approach does not make sense to me. What am I missing?"}, {'account_id': 13719, 'date': '2016-04-21 08:59:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

Devananda,

Thanks for the feedback.

 > For this conversation, I am assuming that users will interact with
 > their cloud through Nova, and _not_ through Ironic. If that is not
 > your starting assumption, please let me know and I will re-read the
 > spec with that in mind.

My starting point is both through Nova and through Ironic standalone.

We have already merged Inject NMI function for Nova KVM during Mitaka
cycle.

http://docs.openstack.org/cli-reference/nova.html#nova-trigger-crash-dump
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/instance-crash-dump

 > When a Node is placed in maintenance mode, this is a signal to the
 > cloud operator that something is wrong with the _hardware_ and Ironic
 > is no longer able to manage it. Status polling stops. The Node is
 > removed from Nova's resource pool. Certain actions (like provisioning
 > an instance) are not allowed on the Node. The end-user (who created
 > the Nova Instance that is now running on this Node) can not interact
 > with the Ironic API -- and therefore, can not clear the maintenance
 > mode flag. 
 > 
 > So, this approach does not make sense to me. What am I missing?

Okay, I understand that maintenance mode doesn't make sense from Nova's
point of view.

In order to be consistent with Nova, I think the current spec of
Inject NMI for Ironic should be acceptable for both Nova and Ironic
user.

Because Nova 'instance-crash-dump' command is asynchronous, executing
the command doesn't wait for completing the Inject NMI dump task, nova
user has to do ssh login or console login to see if reboot has
completed or error has occurred.

WDYT?

If we can agree, I'll submit an updated patch set by reflecting minor
comments.

Best regards,
Naohiro"}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2016-04-21 15:10:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24: Code-Review-1

Cheers,
Lucas"}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2016-06-17 15:58:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29:

Also, the interface with nova "nova inject-nmi" seems to also relies on a reboot [0], so I think that interface-wise we are grand with it as proposed.

[0] https://specs.openstack.org/openstack/nova-specs/specs/liberty/approved/inject-nmi.html#proposed-change'}, {'account_id': 7080, 'date': '2016-06-17 16:40:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

As mentioned inline, I think NMI should be part of the management interface. The improvements proposed to the power control (soft vs hard) are great and enhancing get_supported_power_states is a good way to ensure we can still have drivers not supporting soft modes.

Given how Nova will (in the future) call Ironic with "soft" controls, is it planned that drivers without soft support (e.g. SNMP) fall back to hard controls?'}, {'account_id': 7080, 'date': '2016-06-17 16:49:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29:

Edit: If issuing NMI indeed always reboots the machine, I would suggest something like issuing a soft reboot with NMI being an option (e.g. ironic node-set-power-state NODE soft-off --nmi).'}, {'account_id': 13719, 'date': '2016-06-22 00:26:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29:

Dmitry, Sam, Lucas, Mathieu,

Thanks for the kind reviews.
In terms of the NMI interface, I found that the redfish API 1.0 also
deals with NMI as a part of power control.
So taking the same way as redfish and ipmitool must be quit natural
for Ironic users.
WDYT?

Redfish Scalable Platforms Management API Specification Version: 1.0.0
https://www.dmtf.org/sites/default/files/standards/documents/DSP0266_1.0.0.pdf

P.25

 "Actions" : {
     "#ComputerSystem.Reset": {
         "target":"/redfish/v1/Systems/1/Actions/ComputerSystem.Reset",
         "ResetType@Redfish.AllowableValues": [
             "On",
             "ForceOff",
             "GracefulRestart",
             "GracefulShutdown",
             "ForceRestart",
             "Nmi",
             "ForceOn",
             "PushPowerButton"
         ]
     }
 }

You can see the definition without opening PDF too.
https://github.com/uggla/alexandria/blob/master/alexandria/model/redfish/0.96/Resource.0.96.0.json#L49-L59

Best regards,
Naohiro'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2016-06-22 14:39:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 29:

Thanks for pointing that out @Naohiro,

I'm keeping my vote, it's possible to argue on both sides but due the fact that ipmitool has it as a power action, nova does expect a reboot from injecting nmi (a power change) and now redfish also does have it as a power action, I think Ironic can safely keep it as-in."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2016-06-22 14:48:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 29:

I'm fine with this approach as well. I'm not sure what we should do if the node just halts after NMI though. I'll defer voting to after the discussion on the midcycle anyway."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2016-06-22 15:39:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 29: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

I don't have a strong opinion on power vs management interface, but I have some minor comments - please see inline."}, {'account_id': 6637, 'date': '2016-06-22 15:51:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29:

I prefer NMI in management interface'}, {'account_id': 7080, 'date': '2016-06-22 15:53:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29:

I still stand on the management side. My reasoning:
* Issuing an NMI has undefined power state consequences for generic BMCs
* One might want to be able to use NMI when a different power driver, like SNMP.
* Having NMI in management is exactly like going to a shell and issuing "ipmitool $HOST power diag"'}, {'account_id': 6637, 'date': '2016-06-22 15:53:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29:

The reason I prefer management is because NMI is a fire and forgot command, and power state changes are tracked in by Ironic.'}, {'account_id': 8125, 'date': '2016-06-22 15:54:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 29: Code-Review-1

After hearing the opinions in the midcycle, I think the management interface is better suited for this capability, especially since existing hardware isn't going anywhere and I think consistency is best."}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2016-06-22 15:55:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29: Code-Review-1

I think that the NMI needs to be on the management interface. Power interface commands are all tracked for completion and error, and NMI cannot be tracked as such.

We should just be sending the NMI interrupt, and letting the user (and the power sync loop) handle the resulting power state.'}, {'account_id': 12356, 'date': '2016-06-22 15:58:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29: Code-Review-1

Management interface makes more sense to me too.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2016-06-22 16:01:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29: Code-Review-1

Revoking my vote after the midcycle agreement'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2016-06-22 16:28:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29: Code-Review-1

(10 comments)

Another reason to put INJECT_NMI on the management interface: some operators may want to limit access to this function (using keystone policy settings) separately from power on/off controls.'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2016-06-22 22:25:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 29: Code-Review-1

So based on the way ironic has implemented the power interface, NMI doesn't fit into that model, even though one might think of 'power' when thinking of nmi. The management interface seems to be the best fit for it.

I didn't read all the comments, but has there been consideration about when to allow a user to request an NMI? It seems like it is related to maintenance mode; eg, only allow it if the node is in maintenance mode; or even put the node in maintenance mode if an nmi request is made."}, {'account_id': 13719, 'date': '2016-06-23 08:29:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 29:

Thanks all of you for the kind reviews, I'm going to move NMI to Management I/F as we agreed in the mid cycle."}, {'account_id': 13719, 'date': '2016-06-27 06:13:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29:

commit_message:
Enhance Driver Interface for Soft Power Off and Inject NMI

This specification proposes the work required to enhance the driver
interface to support soft power off and diagnostic interrupt (NMI [1]),
and the work required to provide ipmitool reference implementation.

[1] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-maskable_interrupt

Change-Id: I3dc6561ea7cecf8b8d998717fefa9cf8001d0f4c
Partial-Bug: #1526226

commit_message:
Always run linters for OpenStack-Ansible jobs

Currently any changes in the docs/releasenotes folders do not get
lint checked. While this is generally fine, the sphinx configuration
should be lint checked.

This patch ensures that the 'linters' check runs against any
documentation/releasenotes changes to ensure that this is covered.

Change-Id: I012756f08d52b9757b36912a66154dd42ae0afbe

commit_message:
Quota Update

Exposes the existing Quotas.update call in the management API to
the user API and implements a corresponding shell command.  Admin
privileges will be required to execute the command.

Change-Id: I7cc19a9d2c034bb4b0695cacf7e1bc18a4fd999f

commit_message:
Added tests for "cluster template" and "cluster" commands for Sahara CLI

Tests for "cluster-template" command include their creating, updating,
showing, deleting and list of all cluster templates. Tests for "cluster"
command include create, update, delete and list commands. Also test
for node group creating was updated.

Change-Id: I4bc4b089f2cde8052aa20d1772d5a0530540067e

commit_message:
Modifying call to initActions() to match Horizon

registry.initActions() is moving to the resource type, so in this patch
we adapt by fetching the type (and if it's not present, no harm done) and
calling initActions() on it.

Also accommodating removal of .format() from ResourceType and renaming
of other functions.

Change-Id: Ie8ceb501f81a1a4b3d22adc28b4507f618fd92d7
Depends-On: I1b80971a4b19f26455dfc568de6bbb36b1245ef3
Closes-Bug: 1593795

commit_message:
Use plugins repo version of the human_log callback plugin

With the implementation of https://review.openstack.org/321331 the
human_log callback plugin is now part of the plugins repo.

the version from the plugins repo instead.

commit_message:
Use plugins repo version of the human_log callback plugin

With the implementation of https://review.openstack.org/321331 the
human_log callback plugin is now part of the plugins repo.

This patch removes the retrofitted version in tox in favor of using
the version from the plugins repo instead.

Change-Id: I7db2a37ae62d20f2ac2711877210a6c439aa612f

commit_message:
Use plugins repo version of the human_log callback plugin

With the implementation of https://review.openstack.org/321331 the
human_log callback plugin is now part of the plugins repo.

This patch removes the retrofitted version in tox in favor of using
the version from the plugins repo instead.

Change-Id: I1da09595ddf23750fb9a5278ad2a29474cd1de55

commit_message:
add email notifications for release-post queue

When tags are being proposed by a job running in the post queue, we'll
want to monitor that job for failures. Set up the release-post queue to
use the same email notification that we have for the tag queue.

Change-Id: I045db9173938fbbcaf6c708cfb4677b8122acbf8
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Use plugins repo version of the human_log callback plugin

With the implementation of https://review.openstack.org/321331 the
human_log callback plugin is now part of the plugins repo.

This patch removes the retrofitted version in tox in favor of using
the version from the plugins repo instead.

Change-Id: I173f065f004d3336f6249625c8c36a609742389e

commit_message:
install tempest-horizon from source

Tempest test for Horizon moved from Tempest to a dedicated plugin,
called tempest-horizon. The plugin is currently not packaged in RDO or
UCA but will be soon.
Until this time, deploy the plugin from source.

Change-Id: I509c044a874b77ae0f26d6c7938869fb0c492d87

commit_message:
Add bandit to pep8 venv

Bandit is considered a linter much like pep8. So by request from
the infra team, the bandit job is being made part of pep8 venv.
The bandit testenv needs to stay however for the bandit integration
job.

Change-Id: I83d27217a9ffe8a882342442072272a250eb818c

commit_message:
Add options for configuring file limits in swift

Options have been added to allow a deployer to control the
hard, soft, and fs.file-max limits on swift specific nodes.

Change-Id: Ia5dd51fa360745a9776d58d0bf49d8e1201d3139
Closes-Bug: #1595290
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit 022b62fc8dd7e69adb8cce2858c3203ff81a131b)

commit_message:
Use plugins repo version of the human_log callback plugin

With the implementation of https://review.openstack.org/321331 the
human_log callback plugin is now part of the plugins repo.

This patch removes the retrofitted version in tox in favor of using
the version from the plugins repo instead.

commit_message:
Use plugins repo version of the human_log callback plugin

With the implementation of https://review.openstack.org/321331 the
human_log callback plugin is now part of the plugins repo.

This patch removes the retrofitted version in tox in favor of using
the version from the plugins repo instead.

Change-Id: Id49b469fcb706da1181a3b65baa130c88b44fe56

commit_message:
force a fuller update of the repo being cloned for tagging

zuul-cloner may be using an out of date cache, and may have pointed
originally at a repo on a zuul merger that doesn't have all tags. Force
an update of all remotes and fetch all tags to make sure they are
present before we start trying to add any new ones.

Change-Id: I29cdae3ff8195e4b7e35ac486429394f17919bff
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

commit_message:
Clone grenade for multinode linuxbridge job

The PROJECTS envvar was not updated, so grenade tree was not really
cloned, resulting in job failure.

Change-Id: Iae69f456d790a4d7a29ffbfac71726b860e0fb37

commit_message:
Override install_command in neutron unit tests for periodic queue

Otherwise the command that tries to install upper-constraints is picked
up, and that makes the local and global requirements on neutron-lib clash.

Change-Id: Iba6161497bd7d2152d48fdcf77edfb17893a4232

commit_message:
[CI Fix] Hotfix for stable/liberty jobs

Tempest is branchless, but highly tempestuous in itself.
We have had many breakages in the manila stable branch jobs
because of changes made to the clients that we use for tempest.
This led us to pin a particular commit of tempest. However, when
the changes made to tempest are taken to stable branches of
devstack in any form [1], our stable branch jobs are no longer
protected by the 'stable' commit that we checkout. Without
bringing in the horde of changes to our stable branch, we could
cherry-pick the offending tempest change [2] on top of the
existing 'stable' commit.

[1] I63658b8d8dfa999e0feb79f8f2968f2b32e3ff57
[2] Iab2e6e04b6c5795a4d0c8214564106525b942308

Closes-Bug: #1603275

Change-Id: I4248c704256fc790082f3ac2515c6445ac7aa78a

commit_message:
[Monasca-agent] Remove check-requirements check job for monasca-agent

Remove this CI job because there are libraries such as tornado and
supervisor that we can not get into global requirements. Needs more
work on monasca-agent before we can make it into projects.txt

Change-Id: Ib758cb864835a04ece4c7ff70df359740bb50dd1

commit_message:
Revert "Disable all gate jobs for fuel-mirror master"

This reverts commit b42f1f3af329c1da1bebaff0709da35c2a6c3210.

It turned out that disabling all gate jobs also disables us to merge any patches in master to the directory which is still needed. So the best way is to leave pep8 jobs for master and have fake tox target for pep8.

Change-Id: Icfe4f78f4bee7afeecbfef07fb5331d95f4e963c

commit_message:
[mistral] Add check-requirements to mistral-extra

The gate-requirements-tox-validate-projects job is
failing on openstack/requirements because mistral-extra
doesn't have a check-requirements job.  This adds it.

See: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/341543

Change-Id: I69581e08b0f7ad21adfddf4d3265931baf64536a

commit_message:
Add resource for requesting certificates for HAProxy

This resource will be used in both the overcloud and the undercloud,
and can be called in several instances (for public-facing or
internal-facing certificates).

bp tls-via-certmonger

Change-Id: I0410fe0dbbed97d16909e911f7318d78a5bd7d7b

commit_message:
Correct domain parameter value in tests

Previously in tests keystone client method for user creation was called
with domain equal to 'Default', as far as it was supposed to refer to
domain name. However, it really refers to domain id, so value should be
replaced with 'default'.

Closes-Bug:#1603431

Change-Id: Ic7693d74a0ea1a9cdd789d5adc61b07516ac5918

commit_message:
Prints '-' instead of 'None' when data is None

Client prints 'None' when data is None , and client also prints
'None' when data is a string 'None'. But string 'None' is different
to None. To clear the confusion, Client should print '-' instead of
'None' when data is None. Nova Client and Cinder Client has cleared
the confusion.

Change-Id: I90bf30635f6add5be40b6f7df48b1bd6bb370160

commit_message:
Added ability use variables from environment

Now we can export variables for scenario tests or specify
them via flags in run-command. Credentials.yaml is removed.

closes-bug: #1558994
bp: use-env-variables

Change-Id: I64983028ad88f654e9d0ee7147cfd0f16d6ddbe7

commit_message:
Make the field empty instead of outputing 'None'

Client prints 'None' when data is None , and client also prints
'None' when data is a string 'None'. But string 'None' is  different
to None. To clarify the confusion, Client should make the field empty
instead of outputing 'None'. Nova Client and Cinder Client has
clarified the confusion.

Change-Id: I7e3a965e6ae67152bb9ec6ae1a8a3d16287784bd
Related-Bug: #1600556

commit_message:
Prints  '-' instead of 'None' when data is None

Client prints 'None' when data is None , and client also prints
'None' when data is a string 'None'. But string 'None' is  different
to None. To clear the confusion, Client should print '-' instead of
'None' when data is None. Nova Client and Cinder Client has cleared
the confusion.

Change-Id: Icec92a07897f8650e73dc0f67fad9008d55fb25d

commit_message:
Prints  '-' instead of 'None' when data is None

Client prints 'None' when data is None , and client also prints
'None' when data is a string 'None'. But string 'None' is  different
to None. To clarify the confusion, Client should print '-' instead of
'None' when data is None. Nova Client and Cinder Client has clarified
the confusion.

Change-Id: I71a2d105cc49eefd8509eb6712b21c652fcb694d

commit_message:
Prints  '-' instead of 'None' when data is None

Client prints 'None' when data is None , and client also prints
'None' when data is a string 'None'. But string 'None' is  different
to None. To clear the confusion, Client should print '-' instead of
'None' when data is None. Nova Client and Cinder Client has cleared
the confusion.

Change-Id: I6a8908fcb2df39d7f2c5fc4055cc41779d668d6c

commit_message:
Add Python 3.5 classifier and venv

Now that there is a passing gate job, we can claim support for
Python 3.5 in the classifier. This patch also adds the convenience
py35 venv.

commit_message:
Prints  '-' instead of 'None' when data is None

Client prints 'None' when data is None , and client also prints
'None' when data is a string 'None'. But string 'None' is  different
to None. To clear the confusion, Client should print '-' instead of
'None' when data is None. Nova Client and Cinder Client has cleared
the confusion.

Change-Id: I2c9f6aeb4864b3eac7c6ddbfa0ab4fa1c9029e1b

The datatime.total_seconds() has been deprecated for python >= 2.6,
It is replaced by datatime.timedelta.total_seconds.

Change-Id: Ie75a3afcba0dda2a9e7c3da71e055c3d505efd62
'}, {'created': '2015-12-02 01:52:04.000000000', 'message': 'timeutils.total_seconds() is deprecated

This deprecated func is going to be removed starting with 3.1 version of
"oslo_utils" because the datetime.total_seconds() has been deprecated for
python >= 2.6,and is replaced by datetime.timedelta.total_seconds.

Change-Id: Ie75a3afcba0dda2a9e7c3da71e055c3d505efd62
'}]
commit_message:
timeutils.total_seconds() is deprecated

This deprecated func is going to be removed starting with 3.1 version of
"oslo_utils" because the datetime.total_seconds() has been deprecated for
python >= 2.6,and is replaced by datetime.timedelta.total_seconds.

Change-Id: Ie75a3afcba0dda2a9e7c3da71e055c3d505efd62

commit_message:
Prints  '-' instead of 'None' at print_dict()

1. Currently Cinder client output '-' instead of 'None' at print_list()，
   we should output '-' instead of 'None' at print_dict() too.
2. Add unit test fot it.

Change-Id: Ia84e6e5de62f1e8762c75d5606440378f9e3fc28

commit_message:
Add Python 3.5 classifier and venv

Now that there is a passing gate job, we can claim support for
Python 3.5 in the classifier. This patch also adds the convenience
py35 venv.

Change-Id: I4833f097ece5cab3b3f3e86837dfa285cb229663

This commit change restriction for SSH access only from networks
provided on UI instead of all local networks by default.

[{'created': '2016-07-15 05:54:17.000000000', 'message': 'Do not raise NotFound for resource_get_all_* queries

A stack with zero resources is not an exception worthy condition (for
example, a stack being deleted, a stack which really does have zero
resources).

Also its unusual that a collection query function would raise a
NotFound when the result count is zero.

This change fixes that for resource_get_all_by_stack and
resource_get_all_active_by_stack

Change-Id: I3420d5099830f5626095b17c01e9d886b477915c
Related-Bug: #1301320
Related-Bug: #1523748
'}]
commit_message:
Do not raise NotFound for resource_get_all_* queries

A stack with zero resources is not an exception worthy condition (for
example, a stack being deleted, a stack which really does have zero
resources).

Also its unusual that a collection query function would raise a
NotFound when the result count is zero.

This change fixes that for resource_get_all_by_stack and
resource_get_all_active_by_stack

Change-Id: I3420d5099830f5626095b17c01e9d886b477915c
Related-Bug: #1301320
Related-Bug: #1523748

Python 3.5 in the classifier. This patch also adds the convenience
py35 venv.

Change-Id: I554d1923d3af6b8d36f0e848d9411dd3912e0d31

commit_message:
Support charm upgrades to new OS release

An OpenStack principle charm has an 'openstack-origin' configruation option.
This is used to setup the package source for a charm. If a user updates this
option to point at a package repository then the charm can be configured to
automatically upgrade. This patch adds support for this upgrade scenario.

Change-Id: I3a967b8a8f27e9fd1dd5ab0e5e9e110132308d42

commit_message:
Change plugin version 'version' parameter to 'plugin-version'

Currently we have parameter 'version' for specifying plugin version
for creating node group templates and also for listing available
plugins. The problem is that this parameter is global parameter for
getting version of client. So, this patch fixes this confusion.

Change-Id: I89a670188c20e3b20b98b596a3efb8d5997c3214
Closes-bug: #1565775
(cherry picked from commit f02ea8999c79ea9a3e1f515220775bc54838f9d2)

Hey Gage, so it looks like you stumbled onto one of the APIs that won't benefit from schema validation :)

Typically we use schema validation for POST requests, which the Endpoint-Policy APIs don't use. They rely on a set of PUT/DELETE calls to create and delete associations between IDs."}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2016-07-15 04:44:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I took another look at the v3 APIs and it looks like most of them are competed, sorry if i told you otherwise.

On the plus side, it looks like v2 is completely untouched. I've outlined the remaining controllers and their respective APIs below. Give me a ping on IRC if you have any questions :)

-------

/v2.0/users

User create & update in controller -> https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/keystone/identity/controllers.py#L63-L167

User create API -> http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref/identity/v2-ext/index.html?expanded=create-user-admin-extension-detail#create-user-admin-extension

User update API -> http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref/identity/v2-ext/index.html?&expanded=update-user-admin-extension-detail#update-user-admin-extension

-------

/v2.0/tenants

Tenants create & update in controller -> https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/keystone/resource/controllers.py#L88-L124

Tenant create API -> http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref/identity/v2-ext/index.html?&expanded=create-tenant-detail#create-tenant

Tenant update API -> http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref/identity/v2-ext/index.html?&expanded=update-tenant-detail#update-tenant

-------

/v2.0/roles

Role create in controller -> https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/keystone/assignment/controllers.py#L220-L235

Role create in API -> http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref/identity/v2-ext/index.html?&expanded=create-role-admin-extension-detail#create-role-admin-extension

There is no update role in v2.0

-------

/v2.0/services

Service create in controller -> https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/keystone/catalog/controllers.py#L58-L66

Service create in API -> http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref/identity/v2-ext/index.html?expanded=create-service-admin-extension-detail#create-service-admin-extension

There is no update service in v2.0"}, {'account_id': 13063, 'date': '2016-07-15 06:10:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Goga, thanks for working on this.
Yep, schema validation has been completed for V3/V3-EXT APIs, many APIs from V3-EXT don't exactly need the schema validation, so there are not so many work needed as I expected.

It's low priority to pick up V2 APIs, but nice to see they are guarded by schema validation we well."}, {'account_id': 21420, 'date': '2016-07-15 13:29:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Alright, I will take a look at the v2 stuff then, thanks for the replies!  I will also update the blueprint page on launchpad if that is alright.'}, {'account_id': 21420, 'date': '2016-07-15 13:36:51.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This part of the v3 api does not need schema validation'}]

commit_message:
Replaced asserts in tests with more specific ones

I changed asserts with more specific assert methods.
e.g.: from assertTrue(sth == None) to assertIsNone(*)
or assertTrue(isinstance(inst, type)) to assertIsInstace(inst, type)

The code gets more readable, and a better description will
be shown on fail.

Change-Id: Ife823047a0c086b625c973822c39ac3933e6f67d

commit_message:
Correct reraising of exception

When an exception was caught and rethrown, it should call 'raise'
without any arguments because it shows the place where an exception
occured initially instead of place where the exception re-raised.

Change-Id: I69e007566bf26fa2d4b6bcd1f996f4bba9f49049

commit_message:
Prints  '-' instead of 'None' when data is None

Client prints 'None' when data is None , and client also prints
'None' when data is a string 'None'. But string 'None' is  different
to None. To clear the confusion, Client should print '-' instead of
'None' when data is None. Nova Client and Cinder Client has cleared
the confusion.

Change-Id: I596bc8994d5ad6d25bd443c0791e4f3df92fbf0e

commit_message:
Add 'optional' param for mariadb heka conf

If one is using an existing or alternative mysql deployment and sets
enable_mariadb to false, heka would fail to deploy.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: Ieb793e11a40358e5d4fc1f3955f200e2cddef4f5

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-07-14 20:58:03.000000000', 'message': "neutron: destroy VIFs if allocating ports fails

Following on 92a388a1e34559b2ce69d31fdef996ff029495a6 we also
need to rollback VirtualInterfaces that we create if allocation
fails since a reschedule with a pre-existing port will fail
allocation with a duplicate VIF constraint error.

A new test is added for the rollback section being changed
since there isn't an obvious existing test that this could be
worked into.

commit_message:
neutron: destroy VIFs if allocating ports fails

Following on 92a388a1e34559b2ce69d31fdef996ff029495a6 we also
need to rollback VirtualInterfaces that we create if allocation
fails since a reschedule with a pre-existing port will fail
allocation with a duplicate VIF constraint error.

A new test is added for the rollback section being changed
since there isn't an obvious existing test that this could be
worked into.

Change-Id: I04ca4fff319912ce2a8dc07308a3aec1c24dc58c
Closes-Bug: #1603197

Changes mostly make sense. I'm a bit worried about the possibility of extra context in the container listing indicating that there was an etag override that was set to EMPTY_ETAG, though. Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2016-06-16 16:02:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2016-07-07 14:41:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Tim I'm wondering whether to abandon this or not.

I'm not sure I fully understand the threat w.r.t. future SLO listing etags. Yes, an attacker could infer that the etag is for an empty string (from swift_bytes == 0) and would have access to the IV. But as I understand it that is not a problem - AES-CTR is not thought to be vulnerable to known-plaintext attacks (i.e. the attacker could not infer the key).

We are (no longer) using the same IV for multiple etag encryptions, so knowing the ciphertext of an empty etag is not useful for inferring that another ciphertext is that of an empty etag, nor do we in general encrypt empty etags.

So I'm not sure I see the problem with encrypting an SLO empty-string listing etag?"}, {'account_id': 12279, 'date': '2016-07-09 19:31:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

[{'created': '2016-06-08 14:39:49.000000000', 'message': "crypto - Don't encrypt update override etags for empty object

Fix an anomaly where object metadata for an empty object has no
encrypted etag, but if the encrypter received a container update
override etag in footers or headers then it would encrypt that,
so we'd have encrypted metadata in the container listing but not
in the object metadata. (Empty object etags are not encrypted
because the object content is revealed by its size anyway).

This patch changes the override handling to not encrypt override
etags that correspond to an empty object (aka EMPTY_ETAG), with
one exception: if for some reason the received override etag value
is EMPTY_ETAG but there was an object body, then we'll encrypt the
override etag, because it's value is not obvious form the object
size.

Change-Id: I8d7da34d6d98f351f59174883bc4d5ed0416c101
"}]
commit_message:
crypto - Don't encrypt update override etags for empty object

Fix an anomaly where object metadata for an empty object has no
encrypted etag, but if the encrypter received a container update
override etag in footers or headers then it would encrypt that,
so we'd have encrypted metadata in the container listing but not
in the object metadata. (Empty object etags are not encrypted
because the object content is revealed by its size anyway).

This patch changes the override handling to not encrypt override
etags that correspond to an empty object (aka EMPTY_ETAG), with
one exception: if for some reason the received override etag value
is EMPTY_ETAG but there was an object body, then we'll encrypt the
override etag, because it's value is not obvious form the object
size.

Change-Id: I8d7da34d6d98f351f59174883bc4d5ed0416c101

return explicitly InvalidPagination sort key

Since the patch[1] has been Merged, we should return explicitly
InvalidPagination sort key to help user orientation error.

Add "Ramdisk impact" section to spec template

As per the weekly meeting today [1] we have agreed to add a
new section to the spec template for changes that affect the
IPA ramdisk.

[1] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/ironic/2016/ironic.2016-05-23-17.00.log.txt

commit_message:
Remove 'smart' idleness check

This needs further improvement as it does not appear
to be working as expected so for now just revert it back
to the naive (and more expected) behavior for starting up
new workers (and adding them to the worker pool).

Change-Id: Ia9cc4e44c55ea39bc6270ed42b375ca495bf9ec1

Add id_attr to use in wait_for_status method

This patch set adds id_attr to define name of id field
when resource is being updated.

commit_message:
Add the SSH security section to UI

This change adds the new section with new checkbox as a separate
control instead of the toggleable section because of the description
which should be available even if the section is disabled (default).

DocImpact
Change-Id: I34c9907d781b81253ed6942c67b16f8480de3bb5
Partial-Bug: #1419657

commit_message:
Set 'deployed_before' attribute in cluster attributes if not present

Before this change if  master node had been upgraded to Fuel of
versions >= 8.0, attempt to re/deploy existing clusters would have failed
as attributes of those clusters would have lack 'deployed_before' field.

Since processing of the flag is temporary solution it should not be
coded in data base migration logic. Thus the change introduces creating
of the attribute with given value if it is not already present.

Conflicts:
	nailgun/nailgun/test/unit/test_objects.py

Change-Id: I302ddb340d2ecf14b1fa414fda71aa7f32363bdf
Closes-Bug: #1602281
Related-Bug: #1529691
(cherry picked from commit 48ee65f15e346cff46e0bf0cfba9dbe9afe43528)

commit_message:
Add 'deployed_before' flag to cluster that forbids stop deployment

When cluster is successfuly deployed, that is, has 'operational' status,
'deployed_before' key is added to generated attributes of the cluster.
This flag then is used to determine whether stop action is allowed for
the cluster.

Conflicts:
	nailgun/nailgun/objects/cluster.py
	nailgun/nailgun/test/unit/test_objects.py

Change-Id: I8ecfca5819352ac27d7cec91e22f8006d8c3d8de
Closes-Bug: #1529691
(cherry picked from commit e96920644888c46b3091bc6130a4df197c4987b8)

commit_message:
Use plugins repo version of the human_log callback plugin

With the implementation of https://review.openstack.org/321331 the
human_log callback plugin is now part of the plugins repo.

This patch removes the retrofitted version in tox in favor of using
the version from the plugins repo instead.

Change-Id: I5671dcb28277a3942b9c75ab218dd7d476d48bf0

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 13781, 'date': '2016-07-12 00:49:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

My was that this would be a very light guideline that was intended to help standardize on things such as placing the cancel button on the bottom left of modals.  There were also going to be a few sort of high level principles like "design for production scale." IMHO opinion, we're starting to overthink this...

Horizon has had a chance to provide feedback. In fact, four of the reviewers are from that project.

Would like more reviewers from projects like Fuel and Ironic.'}, {'account_id': 10607, 'date': '2016-07-12 11:06:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Lana - I've attended horizon meetings to attempt to gain support, we have a number of reviewers on the list here from the project. Rob (horizon PTL) has also been quite helpful. 
I have emailed every PTL of horizon plug-in projects - with limited response. I'm not entirely too sure if this means we should try harder, or people are just not that interested. I think the difference is we are trying to address a community wide ops problem, rather than simply fill in a docs gap. 
I will email the list out again today and CC you in for reference. 

Piet - I appreciate your reviews. I am going to avoid making continuous iterations for now, I think it is best we have more reviews from outside our team. If you wish to adjust your own comments, please do so."}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2016-07-12 18:46:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

(18 comments)'}, {'account_id': 20060, 'date': '2016-07-13 16:29:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Thanks everyone for your inline comments :) great to see the reviews.
My colleague, Rodrigo, will address these comments shortly - we are not ignoring your questions :)
Thank you
Alex'}, {'account_id': 13781, 'date': '2016-07-14 22:25:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10607, 'date': '2016-07-15 12:08:55.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandoning to follow different approach.
Thank you everyone for taking the time and effort to comment and review! We will be taking this into account and will be still working on producing good GUI (not UI :P) guidelines!'}]

commit_message:
Fix "indexOf", "lastIndexOf" methods length parameter usage

Previously this parameter was processed as if it was "end" parameter.
This patch fixes it and adds appropriate tests.

Change-Id: I2094ea63c760342df68c7a6090d48ee8e89bae4d
Closes-Bug: #1601843

commit_message:
Ignore arch specific binaries in plugin

This change tells rpmbuilder to not fail the build if arch specific
binaries are included as part of the plugin.  This is helpful if a
plugin wants to include a binary and deploy it via puppet or some other
method that will just copy the file.

Change-Id: Ic3ca86671f0a107b47ab68a54938b6f4040c90b2
Closes-Bug: #1578852

[{'created': '2016-05-24 20:22:24.000000000', 'message': "Skip unavailable hosts when distributing keys

The 'Create authorized keys file from host vars' task assumes that every
host within the nova_compute group is available. If any host within that
group is offline, excluded through a limit, or has otherwise failed an
earlier task, it will lead to this task failing for every host.

Add a when clause checking for the existence of the nova_pubkey hostvar
so that the task and remainder of the role can continue when a
nova_compute host is unavailable.

Related-Bug: 1531783
Change-Id: Idec01d13c35632204a2ae0f0a848a0ccc5b34d73
"}]
commit_message:
Skip unavailable hosts when distributing keys

The 'Create authorized keys file from host vars' task assumes that every
host within the nova_compute group is available. If any host within that
group is offline, excluded through a limit, or has otherwise failed an
earlier task, it will lead to this task failing for every host.

Add a when clause checking for the existence of the nova_pubkey hostvar
so that the task and remainder of the role can continue when a
nova_compute host is unavailable.

Related-Bug: 1531783
Change-Id: Idec01d13c35632204a2ae0f0a848a0ccc5b34d73

[{'created': '2016-07-14 09:04:38.000000000', 'message': "Remove get_trust_id_for_request function

This function tries to determine the current trust_id by looking up the
auth_context's token model. If this information was available it would
have been put on the request.context object so we can use that instead.

Change-Id: I7ce33b30f220be619c638c77eeb76503f1af79a7
"}]
commit_message:
Remove get_trust_id_for_request function

This function tries to determine the current trust_id by looking up the
auth_context's token model. If this information was available it would
have been put on the request.context object so we can use that instead.

Change-Id: I7ce33b30f220be619c638c77eeb76503f1af79a7

commit_message:
Add new flag migrate process finishing.

For qa test it is necessary to determine when migration process finished.
For this purposes /not_ready was used. But it has some disadvantages, it
covers not whole migration process. And there was possibility to mistake.
So was added new  flag which appears after finishing of migration. Old
was left because of old tests. Both of them are used only for testing
propouses and don't affect migration process.

Partial-Bug: #1576276
Change-Id: I49b62dc743111cb4c41489c528e48f8d56c2f9df
(cherry picked from commit ecf9c0d908ece88f21202e59c17109ec098321a7)

commit_message:
Update min tox version to 2.0

The commands used by constraints need at least tox 2.0.  Update to
reflect reality, which should help with local running of constraints
targets.

Note: this is a clone of mriedem's manila change [1].

[1] I27348462a21daab479d76b24b48e3a4e017504cc

commit_message:
Set xtrace in devstack/plugin.sh

With xtrace enabled, developers will get detailed info from
devstack.log.
It will be much helpful for trouble shooting.  Further more,
developers can understand how ironic is initial installed,
how some ironic nodes are created with xtrace log.

Change-Id: I9f4e3fe035913ca1b748e9c2391fa9fddcc90228

commit_message:
Log request-id for each api call

Added support to log 'X-Openstack-Request-Id' for each api call.
If glanceclient is used from command line then following log will
be logged on console if --debug flag is used.

DEBUG:glanceclient.common.http:GET call to glance-api for
http://172.26.88.20:9292/v2/schemas/image used request id
req-e0c7c97a-8fc0-4ce3-a669-d0b1eb5d7aae

If python-glanceclient is used in applications (e.g. Nova) then
following log message will be logged in service logs.

DEBUG glanceclient.common.http
[req-be074f1e-1c17-4786-b703-2a221751c8f4 demo demo] GET call to
glance-api for
http://172.26.88.20:9292/v1/images/detail?is_public=none&limit=20
used request id req-9b1dd929-df30-46b2-a8f2-dfd6ffbad3fc

DocImpact:
To use this feature user need to set 'default_log_levels' in third
party application. For example nova uses glance then in nova.conf
'default_log_levels' should be set as below:

default_log_levels = glanceclient=DEBUG

Implements: blueprint log-request-id

commit_message:
Correct reraising of exception

when an exception was caught and rethrown, it should call 'raise'
without any arguments.

Change-Id: Ifedddb352910f8c499c0ca36c2377567c59c1de5

commit_message:
Adds documenation for auth version 3 in Swift backup driver

This adds the onfig options "backup_swift_user_domain",
"backup_swift_project_domain" and "backup_swift_project" to the cinder
flagmapping files. Documentation around "backup_swift_auth_version" is also
updated to reflect auth version 3.

Change-Id: Ia5ebfb068ac1c1d200094ab649ef97da3d307de4
Closes-Bug: #1591619

commit_message:
Make stack deletion work on all branches

Piping yes to heat isn't working properly - we get 141 return
values from the calls, which indicates a pipe failure.  Upon
further review, we can do openstack stack delete --yes on every
branch except liberty, so let's just do that.  Then we don't need
to pipe anything because liberty doesn't have the delete
confirmation functionality.

The wait_for also doesn't work on liberty because the openstack
stack command doesn't exist yet there.  The openstack function
doesn't help because the command is embedded in wait_for.  Instead,
we just need to pass the correct command to wait_for.

Since there's only a couple of instances of this and the split
between heatclient and osc is temporary I'm just copying the logic
where it needs to go.  Once we're all osc it can be removed along
with the openstack function itself.

Change-Id: I31f880c7fccd55fcd233256f3fc1f2fa63024be3

commit_message:
Refactor to a single request for latest apps

Latest apps section did a single request for each app
in the list.
This patch refactors it with only one request for user's
applications using 'in' operator.

Solves the TODO.

Change-Id: I76d9f48de30c7ec0299aad12e402080ea713c0d5
Closes-bug: #1559066
Depends-On: Ibd93233392552699f9fc02e7f1d92542de2597f1

Restructure mistral-extra repo

* "examples" file tree should not be Python packages

Next steps:

Joseph

TBH, I cannot imagine the other reasons of a race condition at this time.
This data loss seems common for me due to async of the disk.'}, {'account_id': 10016, 'date': '2016-07-13 07:48:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Ken'ichi, this test has been running for years without sync or keypair loss. This issue is new."}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2016-07-13 08:51:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

It's inherent in how the test is written. That we have not had an issue running it in the gate or with cirros images on small flavors doesn't mean it's new. (especially given it only runs on the full-ssh job) Think about the problem for a second, we are hard rebooting a server. This is the equivalent of pulling the power cord from the system. There is no chance for a graceful shutdown and the kernel never has an opportunity to write it's fs cache to disk, this can result in lost data which is exactly what we're hitting here. It makes sense that when you use a larger image or a larger flavor that this is more likely because it takes much more time for things to sync in the background."}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2016-07-13 08:58:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Aactually there is a potential bug I just thought about, but it would be image specifc. We might be relying on the cloud-init/guest-agent/glean thing to repopulate the public key data based on config-drive/metadata service on the second startup and on certain images for whatever reason the guest isn't redoing this after the reboot. If this is the case I think forcing a sync is a fair compromise for extra insurance for a potential guest image issue"}, {'account_id': 10016, 'date': '2016-07-13 09:14:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I agree that this use case doesn't really reflect reality. If you don't think there is any underlying issue, I'm fine with this fix :)"}, {'account_id': 17716, 'date': '2016-07-13 16:19:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Add sync to avoid the loss of pub key data

On the hard rebooting test, the pub key data can be loss due to the
immediate rebooting. In addition, the existing scenario test manager
is using 'sync' command to avoid the other data loss.
So this patch adds a 'sync' command call.

Change-Id: Ie55ad394cdbbde100eee45026c1e52a6f2825b77
Closes-Bug: #1583987

Now that there is a passing gate job, we can claim support for
Python 3.5 in the classifier. This patch also adds the convenience
py35 venv.

Change-Id: I9ec09684fccf532084ac0a5acfeeb6e5cb0ae72c

commit_message:
Add key manager parameters

Added needed key manager parameters for volume encryption.
Also moved the api_class parameter from volume.pp to api.pp
because this parameter is used by cinder-api and not cinder-volume

Change-Id: I1f76bb29b79604b131078b9a895516e1f507409f

commit_message:
Add Python 3.5 classifier and venv

Now that there is a passing gate job, we can claim support for
Python 3.5 in the classifier. This patch also adds the convenience
py35 venv.

Change-Id: I4bc6f28411b4eee1df62a845e70d24c3cfbf500e

will use PXE boot again.

'}]
commit_message:
Update bare metal trust spec to reflect the current solution.

Bare metal trust only support PXE because the way using iPXE
will use PXE boot again.
Bare metal trust will verify the trust states of nodes by passing
a script when booting instead of running a clean task.

Change-Id: I41470bf198cd68d78317e9da7373d650683819d3

I think on-failure is the correct setting for log collection because, as new users start using ironic, this is the most helpful ("sane") default value.

If the aspiring new operator tries to deploy something, it fails, and there are no logs... they will need to go digging through documentation or sample config files to see what option to turn on just so they can get logs when they retry the failing deploy. I believe that is not a good user experience.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2016-07-12 09:20:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Hi @deva,

Yeah I agree that "on_failure" is a better default. I changed it to "never" because I was thinking about the consequences of filling someone's hard disks with logs as part of an upgrade. Tho, the logs are quite small at the moment (since they are gzipped).

I will submit a new patch-set only changing the file's name template.

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-06-30 16:27:01.000000000', 'message': 'Small changes to collect system logs from IPA spec

This patch introduces small changes to the collect system logs spec that
was captured at implementation time. The changes are:

* Replace the slash ('/') in the file name timestamp with a dash ('-'),
  because the linux filesystems does not support the '/' symbol in the
  file names.

* Change the default of when to collect the logs from "on_failure" to
  "never". Enabling collecting logs should be an operator call, logs can
  potentially fill up all the disk space and operators might want to
  be aware of it before enabling such a feature.

Change-Id: I915d236fb3c024be3da881f91342f80e5b4a6ee5
'}, {'created': '2016-07-12 09:23:05.000000000', 'message': "Collect system logs specs: Change the file name template

This patch is replacing the slash ('/') in the file name timestamp with
a dash ('-') because the linux filesystems do not support having a '/'
as part of the file names.

Change-Id: I915d236fb3c024be3da881f91342f80e5b4a6ee5
"}]
commit_message:
Collect system logs specs: Change the file name template

This patch is replacing the slash ('/') in the file name timestamp with
a dash ('-') because the linux filesystems do not support having a '/'
as part of the file names.

Change-Id: I915d236fb3c024be3da881f91342f80e5b4a6ee5

commit_message:
[DOCS] Adding in note for pretend_min_part_hours_passed

After careful consideration, this was the best placement
for this addition. It does not fit into the swift config
files, nor the dev docs or openstack-manuals.
Open to suggestion, but this is my recommendation.

Change-Id: I945c1852a8e3e1a317bd6550b077ab24dd937eb8

1) Please add 'related-bug' and mention the dashboard bug you're working at.
2) Please add a reno note and add this feature to the features list

commit_message:
Add filter based on 'in' operator

This patch makes possible to filter operator values 'id', 'category' and 'tag'
by provided comma-separated values whithin 'in' operator.

F.E. with filter '/a/b?id=in:buzz,bar' 'id' must be among
'buzz' and 'bar' values.

Related-bug: #1559066

Change-Id: Ibd93233392552699f9fc02e7f1d92542de2597f1

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-06-27 14:38:50.000000000', 'message': "Elasticsearch removing from fuel-stats analytics

We don't use Elasticsearch for flexible reports generation on the
fuel-stats web UI, only for five fixed reports. Thus using of
Elasticsearch is overhead and it can be removed from the servers
Instad of Elasticsearch we use fuel-stats json api calls and
PostgreSQL + Memcached.

Changes list:

 - api call added to fuel-stats json api for data required on the web UI page,
 - column release added to DB installation_structures table schema,
 - memcached is used for caching data for the web UI page,
 - elasticsearch client removed from js requirement,
 - web UI page rewritten to use fuel-stats json api instead Elaticsearch.

Change-Id: Ie752e0d0a3c80933888f986e2497b45adce730c9
Closes-Bug: #1595548

commit_message:
Elasticsearch removing from fuel-stats analytics

We don't use Elasticsearch for flexible reports generation on the
fuel-stats web UI, only for five fixed reports. Thus using of
Elasticsearch is overhead and it can be removed from the servers
Instead of Elasticsearch we use fuel-stats json api calls and
PostgreSQL + Memcached.

Changes list:

 - api call added to fuel-stats json api for data required on the web UI page,
 - column release added to DB installation_structures table schema,
 - memcached is used for caching data for the web UI page,
 - elasticsearch client removed from js requirement,
 - web UI page rewritten to use fuel-stats json api instead Elaticsearch.

Co-Authored-By: Kate Pimenova <kpimenova@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: Ie752e0d0a3c80933888f986e2497b45adce730c9
Closes-Bug: #1595548

commit_message:
Install crudini in overcloud again

We had crudini installed before due to some dependency probably, but
either we're no longer installing the package that depended on crudini,
or that dependency was removed, so we need to pull in crudini explicitly
to make sure we can still use it.

Our overcloud upgrade scripts rely on the crudini tool to perform
one-off config tweaks during major upgrades.

Change-Id: I8244ed3199a880b8c26a3e43c80728e650c3ad20
