commit_message:
Clear primary roles during upgrade of nodes

This patch clears primary_roles of a node during its reassignment as a
part of an upgrade. Without this fix it is possible to have several
primary roles in a seed cluster during the upgrade. This race condition
leads to some failed deployments during the upgrade. As a result primary
roles have to be cleared during the reassignment of nodes. That allows
to assign primary roles on appropriate nodes rely on the internal logic.

Related-bug: 1599837
Change-Id: Iae5f3090cfbfd1e6033b94720694a94477562328

commit_message:
New contains_legacy_tasks plugin attribute

In order to warn users about plugin containing legacy tasks which are
not executed unless propagate_task_deploy cluster attribte is set UI
need this attribute.

Change-Id: I024dc20e6e34bd3979fc532cdbd85f77f0bb0a6e
Partial-Bug: #1596928

commit_message:
Deploy full net-iso environment

Add the necessary networks and ports to the quintupleo env file so
that we can start testing with net-iso in OVB envs.

Change-Id: I444395dd48ed77d0e7f382cb3ff781e4b92af402

commit_message:
Update to use quintupleo

Deploying the testenvs with the quintupleo templates in OVB will
allow us to start enabling features like net-iso.

Change-Id: I9abfcafbda51b34f46ca3255c075edeed817e3c3

sqlalchemy: allow to upgrade schema from Ceilometer Liberty

This should allow to upgrade database schemas from Ceilometer Liberty
without much trouble.

Remove the wrong method from MigrateMaintenanceHost

The tables.LinkAction do not have 'action_present' and
'action_past' method. So remove it.

Change-Id: I002f61a35159f7ae97e781f50920fdbbb71e9d94

commit_message:
package-installs: add list to arch and "not-arch" list

Icf8a075224833fcfbbe2128e8802ff41c39f3c09 looked rather ugly, and it's
easy for us to expand the processing done in the arch list.

Change "arch" to a comma-separated list of architectures that should
match for install.

Add a "not-arch" list which will exclude the package from installation
on those architectures.  (An aside -- I considered making it just he
one list with foo,!bar,moo but ! has special meaning in YAML, so it's
easier to have two lists).

$ ARCH=ppc64 package-installs-squash --elements ironic-agent --path=./elements/ /dev/stdout | grep dmidecode
$ ARCH=ppc64 package-installs-squash --elements ironic-agent --path=./elements/ /dev/stdout | grep lshw
    "lshw",
$ ARCH=amd64 package-installs-squash --elements ironic-agent --path=./elements/ /dev/stdout | grep lshw
$ ARCH=amd64 package-installs-squash --elements ironic-agent --path=./elements/ /dev/stdout | grep dmidecode
    "dmidecode",

Change-Id: Ic69dd02a09e6f3ba9078a2377d8df29871a20db2

commit_message:
Fixup os-collect-config unit file so it won't fail on update

An older version of the occ package for rhel can't be updated via
heat causing the upgrade to hang. This makes it so occ can be
updated without interrupting what it was originally doing
(updating itself) with changes to the unit file, delivered
as part of UpgradeInit

Change-Id: Id062279e67a36e94d4155fb6658c1702017dd0a1
Closes-Bug: 1603144

commit_message:
Catch GlanceMetadataNotFound in creating cgsnp

When creating cgsnapshot, Cinder will copy
bootable volume's image metadata to snapshot,
but if the volume doesn't have image metadata,
Cinder should catch GlanceMetadataNotFound
and let it pass, but now Cinder only catch
CinderException and raise it.

This is inconsistency with creating snapshot.

Change-Id: I52a6183af149440434296a16c1717f53d7fc1dc0
Closes-Bug: #1567211

commit_message:
Implement ExecResult class for execution results store istead of dict usage

1. Implement ExecResult class and cover it by unit tests
2. Migrate SSHClient on it

  ExecResult class implements automatic deserialization of ssh output
  (stdout & stderrto string, yand shstring (7 lines max)
  Standard data (exit code, command, stdout & stderr) also stored.
  Also this objace allow 2 ways access to data
    getattr (as normal object)
    getitem (backward compatibilitests)

Later this class is planned to re-use for subprocess helper.

Blueprint: sshmanager-integration
Change-Id: I0e630dc898fb1b476b4d277ce3867ae3513d248f
(cherry picked from commit 3f4d005)

commit_message:
Add python-neutronclient to OSC plugins

Neutron is transitioning its CLI to OSC. Some CLIs will reside
within python-openstackclient while others will be OSC plugins
within python-neutronclient.

Depends-On: I9a20bc7a3d8aa7b631fb0fd534fc5705c23326ce
Change-Id: I2d8d369739d1df1597201368dd2158e07c8d2baf
Related-Bug: #1521291

commit_message:
Perf Optimizations

This patch starts down the road to automated performance
tuning.  It attempts to identify optimal settings for
hard drives and network cards and then persist them
for reboots.  It is conservative but configurable via
config.yaml settings.

Change-Id: Id4e72ae13ec3cb594e667f57e8cc70b7e18af15b

commit_message:
Support the OpenStack-API-Version header

Magnum uses the X-OpenStack-API-Version header for its
microversion header. The X-Header naming scheme is deprecated.
The microversion spec states that OpenStack-API-Version should
be used for the microversion header.

Change-Id: I5b232f65f487d7de15044b8674bf285b2f296bcd
Closes-Bug: #1590595

commit_message:
Add new cluster-network config option

Adds support for specifying a cluster network. This allows
percona replication to be directed onto a specific network
as opposed to always being on the unit private-address network.

Change-Id: If35792f3c6f03533b44fc2c3eae0b192255349e4
Closes-Bug: 1599447

commit_message:
Fix S3 support, register endpoint in keystone

This change registers the configured S3 proxy with Keystone, so that
your cloud knows about the S3 endpoints.

Also includes an update to ensure that the s3token middleware
authenticates against the correct keystone endpoint.

Change-Id: I07d25df6332028a99e0bf79b39f998f84613a4fc

Enable py35 voting on neutron-vpnaas

The py35 job runs without error on the project neutron-vpnaas,
therefore we can safely enabling voting. Reference patch:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/342142/

commit_message:
Remove Icehouse and Juno content from sitemap

Icehouse and Juno docs should not be accesed, so this updates the sitemap
generator tool to skip them. The sitemap can then be regenerated.

Partial-Bug: #1602647
Change-Id: I3117b114881c3a12b6a1a9565a0a720c9c8678b1

Update identity endpoint in v3 and v3-ext samples

Change 'http://localhost:5000/v3', 'http://localhost:35357/v3' and
'http://identity:35357/v3' to 'http://example.com/identity/v3'.

commit_message:
Add optional exceptions regex to avoid to retry.

This is useful when the user (a puppet provider) is expecting a error.
With this it doesn't have to wait for the long retry cycle to have its
error back.  This replace the awkward mechanism in
self.request_without_retry which was dynamically mangling
request_timeout and disabled even legit retry.

Examples of such function are self.fetch_user, self.fetch_project in the
keystone provider.

Change-Id: I589da0100ad3ccf3abf17ac8b26c827793ace484
Related-Bug: 1597357
(cherry picked from commit 806f31d740ac96c15bd26e3f776ce6f008757d37)

commit_message:
Use to_policy_values from context for policy

The oslo.context to_policy_values provide the standard arguments that
should be passed to oslo.policy for enforcement. By using these values
heat will automatically gain support for new things like
is_admin_project as they are supported by oslo_context.

Because previously the whole to_dict was passed to policy enforcement we
are actually removing a whole bunch of options that could be used in
policy enforcement - however from a practical perspective i'm not sure
anyone would have used them.

Closes-Bug: #1602081
Change-Id: I244ed767e2077cf43d55104779484b64bd28c85f

commit_message:
Add __ne__ built-in function

In Python 3 __ne__ by default delegates to __eq__ and inverts the
result, but in Python 2 they urge you to define __ne__ when you
define __eq__ for it to work properly [1].There are no implied
relationships among the comparison operators. The truth of x==y
does not imply that x!=y is false. Accordingly, when defining
__eq__(), one should also define __ne__() so that the operators
will behave as expected.
[1]https://docs.python.org/2/reference/datamodel.html#object.__ne__

Change-Id: Ia6bc60142d2c7368d8b5cf9e6fcf99a0f6e7a072

commit_message:
Rename package mistral.engine.rpc to mistral.engine.rpc_backend

There is a small issue during changing branch from current to Mitaka, where
there was module called rpc.py, and currently there is a package rpc. Problem
is, if Mistral from master was already at least run once, and changed back to
Mitaka, there is a chance, that directory rpc still exists, and contains pyc
files. Trying to use old rpc module will fail with unable to find
get_transport method due remains of bytecode from master branch.

Simple solution for this situation is to rename rpc module to rpc_backend.

Change-Id: Ib5d05930a9715caf2bb5ce1dba4e520a503bc0cd

[{'created': '2016-07-01 09:37:41.000000000', 'message': 'py3: Fix using filter() for python2,3 compatibility

As mentioned in [1], filter() if a list is needed on Python 3:
Replace filter(lambda obj: test(obj), data) with
[obj for obj in data if test(obj)].
[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3

partial blueprint heat-python34-support

Change-Id: I510225570dd0ce252f31cf3c40946a84f5fba82f
'}]
commit_message:
py3: Fix using filter() for python2,3 compatibility

As mentioned in [1], filter() if a list is needed on Python 3:
Replace filter(lambda obj: test(obj), data) with
[obj for obj in data if test(obj)].
[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3

partial blueprint heat-python34-support

Change-Id: I510225570dd0ce252f31cf3c40946a84f5fba82f

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-07-04 07:55:54.000000000', 'message': 'Add __ne__ built-in function

In Python 3 __ne__ by default delegates to __eq__ and inverts the
result, but in Python 2 they urge you to define __ne__ when you
define __eq__ for it to work properly [1].There are no implied
relationships among the comparison operators. The truth of x==y
does not imply that x!=y is false. Accordingly, when defining
__eq__(), one should also define __ne__() so that the operators
will behave as expected.
[1]https://docs.python.org/2/reference/datamodel.html#object.__ne__

Change-Id: I90b7a3dde913646af7a70885fa6054a80c355525
'}]
commit_message:
Add __ne__ built-in function

In Python 3 __ne__ by default delegates to __eq__ and inverts the
result, but in Python 2 they urge you to define __ne__ when you
define __eq__ for it to work properly [1].There are no implied
relationships among the comparison operators. The truth of x==y
does not imply that x!=y is false. Accordingly, when defining
__eq__(), one should also define __ne__() so that the operators
will behave as expected.
[1]https://docs.python.org/2/reference/datamodel.html#object.__ne__

Change-Id: I90b7a3dde913646af7a70885fa6054a80c355525

commit_message:
Add Synology DSM storage driver

This driver supports below features:
- Volume Create/Delete
- Volume Attach/Detach
- Snapshot Create/Delete
- Create Volume from Snapshot
- Get Volume Stats
- Copy Image to Volume
- Copy Volume to Image
- Clone Volume
- Extend Volume

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint synology-cinder-driver
Co-Authored-By: Taylor Huang<taylorh@synology.com>

Change-Id: I18d47f5d4cf10e4f481722406c6a5c071a521616

commit_message:
Turn zmq gates to voting

According to oslo.messaging policy we need transport driver testing
gates to vote, otherwise driver should be removed. This is done
because it is easy to merge code that breaks if there is no gate job
to prevent the merge.

Change-Id: I7198eef2abb08db0b1941103db5e2f63f586dcd0

commit_message:
Revert "Add dbus-1 development libraries"

This reverts commit b8a3924f7e8ef4cdef2a4b43e607948b73806c54.

The few packages that needed this due to keyring and launchpadlib have
now a other-requirements.txt file that includes these libs, so this
addition is not needed anymore.

Change-Id: I7fa508bccc1e39dc2a424cc1a3e972de5f231242

commit_message:
Redirect outdated glossary to up-to-date version

An old glossary is still accessible and showing up in google searches. This
redirects the old glossary to the current version.

TrivialFix
Closes-Bug: #1603171

commit_message:
Install default-jre version for searchlight jobs

Xenial doesn't contain the openjdk-7 package (only openjdk-8).
Searchlight requires a JRE to install Elasticsearch for its CI jobs
and the experimental Xenial job is failing. This patch alters the
Searchlight macro to install default-jre which will use either 7 or 8
depending what's available. Elasticsearch will run fine with either.

Change-Id: I0f63982d7cf64e749dd0c485bfc26ade3c2a9103
Closes-Bug: #1600277

commit_message:
Remove unused context from AuthInfo

The AuthInfo.context attribute is not used anywhere and all the testing
therefore just passes a None value rather than even try and provide real
values. Let's get rid of it.

Change-Id: I7b69b53915def44f531cbda80c875c7b9b114169

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-07-14 17:17:48.000000000', 'message': "Restoring xtrace state for os-brick plugin

The change Ibb7423d243d57852dada0b6298463bbdfc6dc63c that introduced the
os-brick plugin introduced a flaw where the xtrace state wasn't restored
after the end of the plugin's execution. The end behavior is that devstack's
logs were with way less information, difficulting the debugging of the build.
This patch fixes the variable that was intended to hold the xtrace state (it
was using cinder's) and restoring the state at the end of the script.

Change-Id: I47c6c794a9704049b089142eca5603d1183f8a10
"}]
commit_message:
Restoring xtrace state for os-brick plugin

The change Ibb7423d243d57852dada0b6298463bbdfc6dc63c that introduced the
os-brick plugin introduced a flaw where the xtrace state wasn't restored
after the end of the plugin's execution. The end behavior is that devstack's
logs were with way less information, difficulting the debugging of the build.
This patch fixes the variable that was intended to hold the xtrace state (it
was using cinder's) and restoring the state at the end of the script.

Change-Id: I47c6c794a9704049b089142eca5603d1183f8a10

commit_message:
Exclude hashbangs check for .bashrc, .bash_profile, etc

Remove E005 errors for hidden configuration files that do not
end with .sh, e.g., .profile, .bashrc, .bash_profile, etc.

Change-Id: I57d5b556cbc8843b744d3276a1dfdd7467d74fde
Closes-Bug: #1554653

Andreas, we had a long discussion in the team and don't like the idea to create multiple subprojects for many reasons (e.g. we may need many of them and this number will be pretty volatile).

As far as standing up non-standard jobs, actually no specific plan. What are the caveats? Can you please give some hints or direct us to some docs? I thought it's pretty simple: define a job (which runs, for example, tox in some subfolder), define in jenkins and zuul and voila. No?

If you have some strong opinion against our whole idea then please tell more, we may want to change our plans.

Thanks"}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2016-07-14 13:09:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review+2

Renat, I'm fine with starting with one repo and see how it evolves ;)

commit_message:
Change mistral-extra jobs

* Removing python-jobs for mistral-extra because this repo is being
  restructured to have multiple folders with separate potentially
  separate dependencies, jobs to test individual components will be
  set up later as we add them

Change-Id: Id8e5d55e34ec3b3d555b5482e13f99c2561e871e

subject: Flag to enable OpenStack Virtual Baremetal instead of libvirt
messages:
[{'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2016-04-13 05:12:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-04-13 05:12:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/54/304954/1/check/noop/47df1f0/ : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 12715, 'date': '2016-04-14 00:22:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

In general I like this, and the control mechanism proposed here looks good.

A couple thoughts.

- Would be able to develop the ovb role external to this repo and pull it in via ansible-galaxy? We have already done that for the image building role, and eventually I would like to do that for the libvirt role as well.

- Do we have a public cloud we can CI the ovb role against? I know there is one for RDO in the future, but I am not sure how soon the future will be the present.

commit_message:
Flag to enable OpenStack Virtual Baremetal instead of libvirt

This allows quickstart.sh to deploy TripleO via OVB rather than
libvirt. When --ovb is specified, anything tagged libvirt will be
skipped and anything tagged ovb will be run.

The actual OVB playbook is an ansible-galaxy contributed git repositry
(currently a skeleton playbook only)

OVB tasks would differ to the libvirt ones in the following ways
- provision: not needed, the cloud is already there
- environment/setup: not needed, network is created by the heat stack
- libvirt/setup: this would be ansible-role-tripleo-quickstart-ovb
  which creates the ovb heat based on variables provided in the file
  specified by --config
- tripleo/undercloud: should work unmodified, but there may be some
  ovb tagged specific tasks
- tripleo/overcloud: should work unmodified

Change-Id: I8ec0feeee4737141957f015556c5f7b195c1fc86

commit_message:
Use oslo.context's from_environ for creating context

The oslo.context from_environ method is designed to pick up the
environment variables set by auth_token middleware and other common oslo
middleware and correctly set those values on the context object.

By using from_environ context and policy picks up values from the
request without heat having to directly handle them.

The malformed_role tests here are removed. The roles header is provided
by auth_token middleware and now handled by oslo.context and do error
handling their own way. We shouldn't need to test this handling in heat.

Change-Id: I2707bda09a01bf79e75f36b98a48a02adcde5908

commit_message:
Block futurist 0.15.0

This release has a bug that is affecting oslo.messaging
gates and that bug is itself resolved https://review.openstack.org/#/c/341793/
so block this release from being used.

Change-Id: I81beeb625cb92d6e58f3a3249b0d234345576a7c

The neutron server process knows the 'local_ip' value for each L2 agent (as 'tunneling_ip') and can use that information to calculate the appropriate MTU for devices that a particular L2 agent manages. However, it cannot determine whether all L2 agents in the environment should use IPv4 or IPv6 without an additional option that indicates IP version such as 'overlay_ip_version'.

Perhaps we can avoid an additional option by determining the IP version of the environment using the 'tunneling_ip' value from the first L2 agent that registers with the server. Additional agents with mismatching IP versions do not achieve the 'active' state. Furthermore, at some point during initialization, a particular L2 agent attempts to create tunnels to other L2 agents in the environment. Should that agent simply terminate if its 'local_ip' option uses a different IP version than the tunnel endpoints of the other agents?"}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2016-06-07 21:04:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2016-06-07 21:07:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Henry - yes, this still needs more work.  From talking to Matt in irc there are two possible additions here:

1) Determine the IP overlay type automatically from the first agent that registers.  Pro: does not require a new config option; Con: possible edge case where a network is created before we know the IP overlay value.  Personally I like the config option because I think it gives the admin control, and doesn't leave the configuration of this value up to the agent code.

2) Disable (or deny registration?) to an agent where the IP overlay type of 'tunneling_ip' doesn't match what's running.  Maybe that can be a follow-on patch?

This also brings-up another thing - do we need to be able to support different IP overlay types for different tunnel types?  For example, VXLAN over IPv6 coupled with GRE over IPv4 in the same deployment?  If we ever want to do that we're talking RFE.  But in the meantime we should fix this somehow."}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2016-06-08 15:51:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

I think we should only support one local_ip option... thus, supporting only IPv4 or IPv6 for any overlay protocol.'}, {'account_id': 10558, 'date': '2016-06-08 16:44:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I think adding the new overlay_ip_version configuration parameter to neutron-server and validating agent's local_ip at registration is the way go. revisions:
[{'created': '2016-05-23 20:09:42.000000000', 'message': 'Change get_mtu() calculations to support both IPv4 and IPv6

The IPv6 header is twice the size of the IPv4 header, 40 vs 20
bytes, but the tunnel overhead constants are static, only
accounting for an IPv4 header in all cases.  In order to be
correct it needs to treat the tunnel overhead different from
the IP overhead at L3.

This required removing the 20 byte IP overhead from the tunnel
type overhead constants.

It also required centralizing where local_ip is configured in
ml2_conf.ini, removing it from [vxlan] and [ovs] sections and
putting it into [ml2], to reflect the fact they are both using
the same value.  This allows the ML2 code to calculate the IP
address overhead indepenent of the tunnel type overhead.
Those two values are marked for deprecation in the P cycle.

Change-Id: Ia2546c4c71ff48b9fe2817fbad22b1fbf85f325b
Closes-bug: #1584940

'}, {'created': '2016-06-14 21:24:17.000000000', 'message': 'Change tunnel MTU calculation to support IPv6

The IPv6 header is twice the size of the IPv4 header, 40 vs 20
bytes, but the tunnel overhead constants are static, only
accounting for an IPv4 header in all cases.  In order to be
correct it needs to treat the tunnel overhead different from
the IP overhead at L3.

This required removing the 20 byte IP overhead from the tunnel
type overhead constants and creating a new option,
ml2.overlay_ip_version, in order for the server to know which
version will be used, since it calculcates the MTU for the network.

A version mis-match will now cause a tunnel sync to fail.

DocImpact

commit_message:
Change tunnel MTU calculation to support IPv6

The IPv6 header is twice the size of the IPv4 header, 40 vs 20
bytes, but the tunnel overhead constants are static, only
accounting for an IPv4 header in all cases.  In order to be
correct it needs to treat the tunnel overhead different from
the IP overhead at L3.

This required removing the 20 byte IP overhead from the tunnel
type overhead constants and creating a new option,
ml2.overlay_ip_version, in order for the server to know which
version will be used, since it calculates the MTU for the network.
A version mis-match will now cause a tunnel sync to fail on
the server.

Moved all MTU tests to a common location to remove duplication.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ia2546c4c71ff48b9fe2817fbad22b1fbf85f325b
Closes-bug: #1584940

commit_message:
Fix upgrade failure due to missing repo containers

Commit 368b7e2b0ef5abf792373f232087d0a4e595a5b9 has introduced a bug
causing the upgrade script to fail when running the playbook
mariadb-apt-cleanup.yml. The failure happens because the repo containers
no longer exist and so the playbook fails to connect to those
containers.

This commit modifies the hosts targeted by mariadb-apt-cleanup.yml to
remove the repo containers.

Closes-Bug: 1603071
Change-Id: I9c314528e7868376b5fe249efa904b7ee6d53144

commit_message:
Fix delete API of profile/policy/receiver resources

This patch revises implementation of profile/policy/receiver
delete API interfaces: HTTPNoContent exception will be raised
to generate 204 response code. Current implementation based on
extra succeeded code will cause incorrect Content-Length which
should be 0. Related tempest API tests are also improved to
verify this change. This patch also fixes an error that exception
could be incorrectly disguised twice.

Change-Id: I8c3517f9bdc4499d90858b865e6c2d6d43fc810c
Closes-Bug: #1602109

commit_message:
Fix lb healthmonitor delay/timeout unit

This patch changes description of lb healthmonitor
delay/timeout unit from second to millisecond. The
actual unit is millisecond in code implementation
of Neutron-lbaas but existing API reference erroneously
describe it as second. Neutron team has decided to
correct the document rather then fix code implementation
to make them consistent. More discussion can be found
here:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/339260/1

Change-Id: I43bbdf45a7f79f4a52dca0009fa195e9cc03d667

commit_message:
Fix bug "identity service failed when creating the password plugin"

When the KEYSTONE_AUTH_URI is set as
"http://${KEYSTONE_AUTH_HOST}/identity_v2_admin", identity service
in keystone will fail to create the password plugin. It can not
determine a suitable URL for the plugin.



Change-Id: Ia7278000d3bb743136853cc78f9c74524fab43b6
Closes-bug: #1600416

This is the error:

    2016-07-13 11:49:59.478293 | ERROR: the main setup script run by this job failed - exit code: 124
    [...]
    2016-07-13 11:50:31.933530 | [Zuul] standard output/error still open after child exited2016-07-13 11:50:31.933654 | [Zuul] Task exit code: 124
    2016-07-13 11:50:38.503445 | [Zuul] Job complete, result: FAILURE

- - -

Some discussion with Jeremy Stanly on IRC on why the above is happening [minor edits for readability]:

"I think that may be expected on DevStack-based jobs because there are child processes who don't properly disassociate and don't close file descriptors.   At least expected after the zuul 2.5 transition a month or so ago.  If it's the issue i think it is, this has been endemic to DevStack for many years.  The issue is: any time i've tried to execute devstack over an SSH session, SSH doesn't want to disconnect because of open file descriptors

I recall seeing it consistently when doing http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/devstack-gate/tree/README.rst#n95.  I don't recall whether I saw it on interactive SSH sessions or only scripted SSH sessions with no parent TTY.  The symptom is just that when the running process terminates (or you log out of the shell) your ssh socket hangs and you have to manually disconnect it (~. or kill 
from another terminal or whatever)

The error message you're seeing at the end of the log is, i think, bubbling up from ansible's error handling around that condition -- since Zuul launcher is running jobs via Ansible."'}, {'account_id': 6962, 'date': '2016-07-13 17:43:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

[{'created': '2016-07-13 10:37:13.000000000', 'message': 'Remove support for End Of Life (EOL) Fedora 22

Fedora 22 reaches its EOL on 19-JUL-2016[1].  Remove it as
officially supported distribution.

The current two supported Fedora distributions are Fedora 23 and Fedora
24.  (Change Ia4a58de4973ef228735c48b33453a0562dc65258 already added
support for Fedora 24.)

[1] https://fedoramagazine.org/fedora-22-end-of-life-2016-july/

Change-Id: I5b4e1ddb6165a9065e80e84175246678a7356f18
'}]
commit_message:
Remove support for End Of Life (EOL) Fedora 22

Fedora 22 reaches its EOL on 19-JUL-2016[1].  Remove it as
officially supported distribution.

The current two supported Fedora distributions are Fedora 23 and Fedora
24.  (Change Ia4a58de4973ef228735c48b33453a0562dc65258 already added
support for Fedora 24.)

[1] https://fedoramagazine.org/fedora-22-end-of-life-2016-july/

Change-Id: I5b4e1ddb6165a9065e80e84175246678a7356f18

Class base.Resource defines __eq__() built-in function, but does

commit_message:
base.Resource not define __ne__() built-in function

Class base.Resource defines __eq__() built-in function, but does
not define __ne__() built-in function, so self.assertEqual works
but self.assertNotEqual does not work at all in this test case in
python2. This patch fixes it.

Change-Id: I819cb27664661e0b67d1e886c28432a2d1134cb0
Closes-Bug: #1586268

commit_message:
Variables in URL path should be required

These inline parameters are not optional, they are required to call the
API, this patch change all of them from optional to required.

Change-Id: I6b1c8893b12e5e88f887c884b9812eb1005dcbdd

commit_message:
Reduce logging level of API validation messages.

cinder.utils.check_metadata_properties logs validation failures
at warning level, which it really shouldn't - API validation is
not something the admin really cares about.

This patch changes them to debug.

Closes-Bug: #1599732
Change-Id: I33ea67e32a007ff1a3f0b8111b16b1e18cd207e6

Doug,

Just a heads up, we do follow the stable release policy with the kolla deliverable, however, because we rebranched the project tony had indicated he wouldn't approve our tagging as such.  I guess I sort of gave up trying to get that tag, but I'll give it a go, since i think intent matters more then the unnatural acts we had to go through to get the project into a state where it was not dangerous for use by operators.

We do now follow all requirements of stable follows.

Regards
-steve"}]

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-07-13 22:24:43.000000000', 'message': 'Order kolla-kubernetes bootstrap/run/kill commands

Prior, commands such as "kolla-kubernetes bootstrap" command generates
all of the template files for a particular service into a directory
and then does a "kubectl create -f <directory>" on all bootstrap files
at the same time.  This worked fine before, because the templates in
the could be instantiated without regard to order (just pods and svc).
However, multi-node persistence patches will add disk, pv, and pvc
templates which need a very specific order.  This patch maintains the
bootstrap/run/kill commands, but allows these commands to function and
respect order.

Change-Id: If3a00e512f455f9555af78800ef11de0b0ecc869
Partially-implements: blueprint kolla-kubernetes-cli
'}]
commit_message:
Order kolla-kubernetes bootstrap/run/kill commands

Prior, commands such as "kolla-kubernetes bootstrap" command generates
all of the template files for a particular service into a directory
and then does a "kubectl create -f <directory>" on all bootstrap files
at the same time.  This worked fine before, because the templates in
the could be instantiated without regard to order (just pods and svc).
However, multi-node persistence patches will add disk, pv, and pvc
templates which need a very specific order.  This patch maintains the
bootstrap/run/kill commands, but allows these commands to function and
respect order.

Change-Id: If3a00e512f455f9555af78800ef11de0b0ecc869
Partially-implements: blueprint kolla-kubernetes-cli

commit_message:
Follow-up patch of cbe51c6a10d1fa68c7082af67827d8c0d8967fe3

This patch is a follow-up patch of
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/293873/ addressing some of the remaining
comments after the patch was merged. The changes are:
* ironic/drivers/modules/ipmitool.py
  * Add "check_exit_code" parameter to _exec_ipmitool() instead of a kwargs.
  * Fix docstring of get_console().
* Fix release note that adding explanation about new drivers.

Change-Id: I3d269fd461c47d629328eba413eb4f5331a40de1

commit_message:
[cli-ref] Concatenate the command options with '-'

The original command breaks the line between the
command option with hyphen.
But, it looks strange to users.
This patch addresses the issue as work around
until the upstream code will be fixed.

Change-Id: I243c3bc73c65928e893f23308dd288da5d1dc80c
Related-Bug: #1599066

trivial: comment about vif object address field

I always have to check if the VirtualInterface.address
field is an IP or a MAC address, so add a comment about
what it is.

commit_message:
Allow "Other Versions" section to be configurable

Adds a new option that allows the "Other Versions" section to be removed
if a project isn't interested in showing links to older versions. The
default value is False which means that it will be hidden.

Even though the setting is not backward compatible there are enough
broken documentation links in the OpenStack projects that this should be
opt-in behavior.

Change-Id: Ic4b47b19aa9db38557c37aed7722174b7dbdf4a1
Closes-Bug: #1599260

commit_message:
Deprecate baremetal API and CLI interfaces

Nova has a very bad read only baremetal proxy, which we will be
deprecating and removing. This signals this in our client.

Co-Authored-By: Jim Rollenhagen <jim@jimrollenhagen.com>
Change-Id: Icf479c29c0c43d91871f49fe4b71266954b0c3f7

commit_message:
Update Smart-Table to 1.4.13

This is the latest release for 1.x. Moving to this version for now, will
investigate 2.x later

Also adds several missing files so that the package is consistent with
the other xstatic packages.

commit_message:
Implement L2 Communication for ml2 dragonflow driver.

This patch implements L2 communication when ml2 dragonflow driver is used.
With tenant network, segmentation_id of the network is used as tunnel key,
not use port unique key allocated by dragonflow anymore.

Change-Id: Ia706d1eabb4d2faaf60576a7bd252e75cee95c6d

commit_message:
Improve user experience involving token flush

Currently with the use of memcache it is no longer necessary to use
the token_flush command. Running this command with KVS driver enabled
fails and throws a Traceback and NotImplemented errors. For a better
UX, we allow the implementation to pass and log a warning message

Change-Id: I95addc8df3a39135fb3fe3c63b6b21c1c279ace8
Closes-Bug: #1520321

commit_message:
[inspection] allow to configure HTTP port

We currently allow changing the HTTP port for Ironic iPXE support,
but we don't allow the same for ironic-inspector. This patch fixes it.

Change-Id: I62effb9d0196474a3768ef7e80528f730df8a543
Closes-Bug: #1602976

commit_message:
Pass request to normalize_domain_id

The normalize_domain_id function is adding the appropriate domain_id to
users and projects that are allowed to receive this information from a
domain scoped token. Pass a request to this function and use the context
to determine the current scope.

Change-Id: Ia880c6164c63ff08900218ab5947d648638868fa

[{'created': '2016-07-14 08:32:17.000000000', 'message': "Remove a validate_token_bind call

assert_admin is intended to check the roles of the current token to
ensure that there is the admin role. It is basically the v2 equivalent
of @protected for most operations. o

Because keystone requires the auth_context middleware be in the pipeline
we know for any authenticated call a request has passed through this
middleware and so the token bind has already been validated.

"}]
commit_message:
Remove a validate_token_bind call

assert_admin is intended to check the roles of the current token to
ensure that there is the admin role. It is basically the v2 equivalent
of @protected for most operations. o

Because keystone requires the auth_context middleware be in the pipeline
we know for any authenticated call a request has passed through this
middleware and so the token bind has already been validated.

We can therefore remove this secondary call. We probably don't need to
worry about the assert_authenticated call however it will produce a
nicer error message if the middleware is not in place.

Change-Id: I2808f0ca9793e892026f083122d4f7266593c496
